@node "INTRODUCTION" "Introduction"

 INTRODUCTION
 --------------------

 During the development of our PalmSuite for Amiga computers, the PalmLink
 library was released. As we needed to find out if that library gives
 us any gain compared to our connection stack, we quickly adapted some
 tools we got here, to use PalmLink library. The PalmBackup is the
 result of that.

 Formerly, PalmBackup was not intended to be developed after its release.
 But as many people requested some features to be added to this program
 we decided to develope it a bit more. 

@endnode

@node "Functionality" "Functionality"

 PALM BACKUP FEATURES
 --------------------

  · backup of organiser databases
  · restore
  · configurability of almost any option it offers.
  · multi user support
  · internal cache system (once you list your unit, PalmBackup will
    keep the list of the remote files).
  · advanced manager for installing, removing, purging etc
  · fully system compatible
  · quick, fast and efficient code
  · fully localized
  · fast on-the fly text-to-palm-doc converter

@endnode

@node "FAQ" "FAQ"

 FAQ
 ---------------------

 Q: PalmBackup is shareware product. I like it but I've heard about
    PalmSuite software. Even the PalmBackup is a cheap product, I wonder
    if there are any upgrade discounts planned for future PalmSuite,
    for all registered users of PalmBackup?
 A: Yes, there will be special upgrade offer for all registered
    PalmBackup users, no need to worry about. If you want to register
    Palm Backup - go for it, and keep your databases save with
    registered PalmBackup now.

 Q: Can I register on-line?
 A: Yes, of course. Open "About" window and click "Register" button.
    NOTE: you have to have OpenURL.library installed and properly
    configured. But we guess you got it as any other serious user.
    If not ;-) browse: http://www2.viaweb.com/pilotgearsw/wfmh.html

 Q: I can't find any button to activate on-the-fly text converter. Why?
 A: There's no need for any buttons, as the converter works automaticly.
    See  @{" Quick Tour " link QuickTour} for more details how to 
    transfer text files to you PalmPilot

@endnode

@node "QuickTour" "Quick Tour"

 QUICK TOUR
 -----------

  How to start using PalmBackup:
  -----------------------------------

   · download PalmBackup and PalmLink
   · unpack and install it (PalmBackup will run w/o installation
     as well, but we strongly recommend to install it using enclosed
     installer script, which check your environment for needed components
     add required (if missing), update when needed or install only program
     itself, if all other parts are already installed, saving HD space).
   · launch it
   · enter the user editor (via menu, or by clicking 'faces' on toolbar)
   · add yourself to the user list.

     NOTE:  if your unit is already personalised, you MUST enter
            the same name your unit belongs to, otherwise you won't
            be able to backup/restore anything!

     NOTE2: if your unit is not personalised yet, pick up the name
            you want it to be personalised to, because PalmBackup will
            set up the owner while next Backup/Restore operation!

   · if you want to be automatically selected everytime you start
     the program, select 'default profile'.

     NOTE: there's can be only one default profile. For now PalmBackup
           won't prevent you to have more than one while working in
           user editor, but when program load the user list next time,
           only one user profile will remain with 'default' flag set.            
     
   · accept changes and leave the user editor
   · select "Project/Select user" and pick up your name

      NOTE: if you want to have no 'default profiles', you will have
            to select the user to be useed everytime you start the
            program by using this option.            

   · enter "Settings/Backup"
   · click "Scan" to fetch the list of available databases from the unit
   · when done, build the list of files you care about and you want to
     have backuped. We suggest to add all "Generic" databases (those
     which got "Backup on HotSync" flag set (see ICONS chapter below),
     and make sure "ToDoDB", "AddressDB", "DateBookDB" and "MemoDB" are
     on the backup list (if not, add them by hand).
   · accept changes you've made by clicking "OK". Now you 
     are ready to backup your databases.


  To backup selected files:
  -----------------------------------

   · put your unit in the craddle
   · press "Backup" icon -> you'll see the list of files to bacup
   · If you do not want to backup all the files you have selected
     if the Backup preferences, use "All", "None", "Toggle" buttons
     to make subselection (the checkmark on the first column is marked,
     shows the state of the database. When selected, it will be backuped.
     When it's cleared, it will be ommited). By default all databases
     are selected.
   · press "Backup"
   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till backup is finished

      NOTE: every database will be purged after backup (usual
            behaviour)


 To restore your backup:
 -----------------------------------

   · select the backup you want
   · click "Restore" button to see the list of files you are going
     to restore
   · If you do not want to restore all files in the given backup,
     use "All", "None", "Toggle" buttons to make subselection (the
     checkmark on the first column is marked, shows the state of the
     database. When selected, it will be restored. When it's cleared,
     it will be skipped). By default all databases are selected.
   · press "Restore"
   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till restore is completed

      NOTE: databases on unit are overwritten on restore.


 To install any software/files:
 -----------------------------------

   · select "Project/Manager" menu item
   · using the left panel browse to the directory you got the files to install
   · select the file(s) you want to install
   · press "Install"
   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till transfer is completed 


 To use on-the fly text-to-palm-doc converter
 -----------------------------------

   · select "Project/Manager" menu item
   · using the left panel browse to the directory you got the text files you
     want to install. Please note that recently text files needs to have
     ".text" or ".txt" name suffix to be properly recognized
   · select the file(s) you want to install
   · press "Install"
   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till transfer is completed 

     NOTE: the on-the-fly converter works fully automated. Whenever it
           detect you want to upload the text file, it will be activated.
           You can safely mix the text files with other (.prc, .pdb) and
           upload them together at once.          
           


 To fetch (backup) single file(s):
  -----------------------------------

   · select them on the right panel list
   · select destination directory in the left panel
   · press "Fetch"
   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till finished


 To delete any software/files:

   · select them on the right panel list
   · press "Delete"
   · confirm (or not) the operation

       MOTE: this cannot be undone unless you got
             your victims backuped!

   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till finished


 To purge (remove records marked as deleted) any database:
  -----------------------------------

   · select them on the right panel list
   · press "Purge" (there's NO confirmation requester!)

       MOTE: these purged records cannot be restored unless
             you've got your victims backuped! But that's usually
             not a problem ;-)

   · press "HotSync" button when requested
   · wait till finished

@endnode

@node "Extras" "Extras"

 EXTRAS
 --------------------

 While playing with PalmBackup, please consider testing our latest
 release: the PalmIMGV datatype (PalmOS image format!) for all OS3
 Amigas. Using this piece of code, you will be able to view almost
 all PalmPilot images using e.g. Multiview on your desktop machine.
 Please register datatype as well -> your PalmSuite discount will
 be even bigger!

@endnode

@node "Limitations" "Limitations of demo version"

 LIMITATIONS
 --------------------

 Demo of PalmBackup is almost fully featured, so you can taste
 the product before you register it. However, expect some
 obstacles you will have to bear with:

   - annoying nagging requesters
   - backup only 6 databases per session
   - restores only 6 databases per session
   - may expire one day

@endnode

@node "Registrations" "Registrations"

 REGISTRATIONS
 --------------------

 PalmBackup is released under concept of shareware. The registration
 fee is US$ 10 only. For details about "How to register" see the
 'nagging' requester. When registered, you will receive uncrippled
 version. We will also offer special discounts while PalmSuite is out!
 Keep your data safe with PalmBackup now!

@{i} NOTE: Registered users of previous versions can upgrade to v1.6
       for free. Just drop us a mail, giving you details (and, if
       possible your PilotGear's order number)@{ui}

@endnode

@node "Icons" Icons"

 ICONS
 --------------------

 PalmBackup uses small pictograms (mainly in lists). Here's
 the explanation of its meaning:


 USER PROFILE EDITOR

  - "small head", next to the user name indicates the default
    user profile (that user will be automatically logged when
    you run PalmBackup)

 VARIOUS LISTS OF DATABASES

  - "disk" indicates the databases that are marked as "Generic".
    That means the "Backup on next sync" flag is set, and for
    some reasons these files should be fetched. It's recommended
    to backup all "Generic" databases, unless you are absolutely
    sure you know what that file is and you know the reasons
    you don't care about it.

  - "01010" icon next to the database name shows the file is
    of "Resource" type. "Resource" means it's a ordinary program
    (executable), just like, for instance, "PalmBackup" is for
    AmigaOS.

  - "chip" determines ROM files (mainly built-in applications or system
    related files. Those files cannot be removed and there's no need
    to backup them - they won't 'disappear' when you battery die.

  - "!" indicates unexisting databases. You may have the database
    present in your files-to-backup list, but it may be already
    removed from the unit. When PalmBackup is unable to localize
    database while bakcup, the "!" sign appear next to its name.

@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"

 CONFIGURATION
 --------------------

 By default PalmBackup uses serial.device unit 0 at 57600 baud.
 If you want it to use something different (your own MFC, HC etc
 I/O cards), there is special configuration window (Settings/General)
 that allows you adjust these settings.

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs"

 BUGS
 --------------------

 - sometimes the toolbar images remain locked. It seems to be
   MUI related problem/feature, as the only thing PalmBackup does
   with those images is ordering MUI to load and render it.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

 REQUIREMENTS
 --------------------

 Standalone archive is not enough to launch the program.
 You will need as well:

  · AmigaOS 2.x or better
  · PalmPilot organiser (or derivatives)
  · MUI 3.8 or better


 Optional software:

  · OpenURL 2.0 (Aminet:comm/www) to make About window's links work

@endnode

